04288nam a22006615i 9780814768969DE-B159720200608045044.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200608t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013007519  a97808147689697 a10.18574/97808147689692doi  a(DE-B1597)547924  a(OCoLC)1158115453  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPJ7750.A25bR5713 2014eb 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a892.7834081 aal-Ma'arri, Abu l-'Ala, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Epistle of Forgiveness :bVolume Two: Hypocrites, Heretics, and Other Sinners /cAbu l-'Ala al-Ma'arri; Geert Jan van Gelder, Gregor Schoeler. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLibrary of Arabic Literature ;v3600tFrontmatter -- tLetter from the General Editor -- tTable of Contents -- tAbbreviations used in the Introduction and Translation -- tIntroduction -- tNotes to the Introduction -- tOn Hypocrisy -- tThe Sheikh's Return to Aleppo -- tHeretics, Apostates, and Impious Poets -- tOld Age, Grave Sins, Pilgrimages, and Sincere Repentence -- tThe Stolen Dinars and the Number Eighty -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tConcordance with Risālat al-Ghufrān, 9th edition, edited by Bint al-Shāṭiʾ -- tIndex -- tAbout the NYU Abu Dhabi Institute -- tAbout the Typefaces -- tAbout the Editor-Translators 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of themost unusual books in classical Arabic literature, The Epistle of Forgiveness is the lengthy reply by the prolificSyrian poet and prose writer, Abu l-?Ala? al-Ma?arri (d. 449 H/1057 AD), to aletter by an obscure grammarian, Ibn al-Qarih. With biting irony, The Epistle of Forgiveness mocks Ibnal-Qarih's hypocrisy and sycophancy by imagining he has died and arrived withsome difficulty in Heaven, where he meets famous poets and philologists fromthe past. He also glimpses Hell, and converses with the Devil and variousheretics. Al-Ma?arri-a maverick, a vegan, and often branded a heretichimself-seems to mock popular ideas about the Hereafter. This second volume is a point-by-point reply to Ibnal-Qarih's letter using al-Ma?arri's characteristic mixture of erudition,irony, and admonition, enlivened with anecdotes and poems. Among other things,he writes about hypocrites; heretical poets, princes, rebels, and mystics;apostates; piety; superstition; the plight of men of letters; collaborativeauthorship; wine-drinking; old age; repentance; pre-Islamic pilgrimage customs;and money. This remarkable book is the first complete translation in anylanguage, all the more impressive because of al-Ma?arri's highly ornate anddifficult style, his use of rhymed prose, and numerous obscure words andexpressions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aForgiveness of sin. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aGelder, Geert Jan van, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchoeler, Gregor, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814768969423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814768969.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK